* Early childhood (4-6 years): Increased independence in daily activities, such as dressing, eating, and sleeping.
* Middle childhood (7-10 years): Children begin to take on more responsibility, such as helping with household chores and making simple decisions.

* Early adolescence (14-16 years): Children start to assert their independence, such as wanting to spend more time with peers and making their own decisions.
* Late adolescence (17-19 years): Children are considered almost fully independent, with the ability to make their own decisions and take care of themselves.
* Young adulthood (20+ years): Children are considered fully independent and are expected to be self-sufficient and responsible.
